video_description: Reality TV contestants may soon be employees. Once remedied, the case¬†could become the basis for the improved working conditions that reality show stars have long awaited. After the agency worked with two ‚ÄúLove Is Blind‚Äù stars who filed unfair labor practice charges¬†in 2023, the NLRB regional office in Minnesota assigned to the case issued a filing Wednesday. THIS Moon is Constantly ERUPTING No moon in our solar system is likely as chaotic as Io, Jupiter‚Äôs third largest. The rocky body looks like a pepperoni pizza because of the constant, numerous eruptions on its surface. The volcanic activity fills the skies with sulfur dioxide and is constantly changing features on the ground. It‚Äôs the most volcanically active world in our solar neighborhood, and has an impressive r√©sum√© for a place that is only slightly larger than our own moon.‚ÄúIo is one of the most intriguing objects in the whole solar system,‚Äù said Scott Bolton, a director at the Southwest Research Institute. ‚ÄúThis body is completely covered with volcanoes over both poles, all across its middle, constantly going off. So how does this really happen?‚Äù Io‚Äôs volcanic origins have baffled scientists. Many thought a global magma ocean may be percolating under Io‚Äôs surface, a feature that could have been common in the early evolution of planetary bodies in our universe and could explain the wide spread of volcanic activity.

What happened to the electric mail trucks? They‚Äôre way behind schedule. A multibillion-dollar program to buy electric vehicles for the U.S. Postal Service is far behind its original schedule, plagued by manufacturing mishaps and supplier infighting that threaten a cornerstone of outgoing President Joe Biden‚Äôs fight against climate change. The Postal Service is slated to purchase 60,000 ‚ÄúNext Generation Delivery Vehicles,‚Äù or NGDVs ‚Äî mostly electric ‚Äî from defense contractor Oshkosh, which has a long history of producing military and heavy industrial vehicles, but not postal trucks. Congress provided $3 billion for the nearly $10 billion project in the 2022 Inflation Reduction Act, one of Biden‚Äôs chief legislative accomplishments. But as of November, the Postal Service had received only 93 of the Oshkosh trucks, the agency told The Washington Post ‚Äî far fewer than the 3,000 expected by now. Significant manufacturing difficulties that were not disclosed to the Postal Service for more than a year have stymied production, according to internal company records and four people with knowledge of the events, speaking on the condition of anonymity to avoid professional reprisals. Caption from article by Jacob Bogage.

Could MORE Chinese products be banned?! A combination of unique factors has put some Chinese technologies on U.S. lawmakers‚Äô naughty list. Companies from China are increasingly global technology trendsetters, including in important areas like electric vehicles and artificial intelligence. It‚Äôs hard to buy an internet-connected home device that doesn‚Äôt run on Chinese technology. Technologies that originate in other countries considered adversaries of the United States, such as Iran and Russia, are mostly irrelevant in the United States. There‚Äôs also a fuzzy line in China between private corporations and the government. U.S. officials believe that TikTok or other Chinese companies would have to comply if Beijing ordered them to hand over data they have on Americans, to spy on us, or to spread Chinese Communist Party propaganda.

A judge rejected the sale of InfoWars to The Onion (12/11/2024). U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Christopher Lopez ruled Tuesday that the November court-ordered auction of Jones‚Äôs website lacked transparency. The decision capped a two-day hearing that stretched late into the night in U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Christopher Lopez‚Äôs Houston courtroom. ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt think anyone acted in bad faith here. I think everyone was trying to buy an asset and put their best foot forward and play by the rules,‚Äù Lopez said as he delivered his decision. The judge took issue with the lack of transparency from the sealed bidding process selected by¬†the court-appointed trustee Christopher Murray, who was overseeing the sale of Jones‚Äôs assets. The judge added that he was troubled that the process, however well intended, ‚Äúdid not maximize value in any way, based on the record before me.‚Äù In a¬†statement, the Onion‚Äôs CEO, Ben Collins, expressed disappointment that the ruling did not clear a path forward for any bidder, but he indicated it would continue its efforts toward acquiring Infowars. ‚ÄúIt is part of our larger mission to make a better, funnier internet, regardless of the outcome,‚Äù the statement said. Caption from article by Kim Bellware¬†and¬†Niha Masih.

The Murdoch family is fighting over future control of Fox News and the Wall Street Journal. Rupert Murdoch wanted to change the terms of his family‚Äôs trust to ensure that his son Lachlan would be his successor upon his death, but a Nevada probate commissioner rejected his bid. Murdoch, 93, initiated the effort to change the terms of the trust last year to preserve the conservative orientation of his sprawling media empire. As first reported by the New York Times this summer, the elder Murdoch was concerned that a ‚Äúlack of consensus‚Äù among his three other older children would have financial consequences for the company. But probate commissioner Edmund ‚ÄúJoe‚Äù Gorman Jr. ruled against the effort, deeming it a ‚Äúcarefully crafted charade,‚Äù¬†the New York Times reported on Monday afternoon.¬†The case will now move to a district judge who could choose to affirm the recommendation, deny it or send it back for additional inquiry. Caption from original article by Jeremy Barr¬†and¬†Sarah Ellison.
